# Context

When the customer types a promo code in the dedicated promo step, the PWA can validate it before continuing. This endpoint returns whether the code is valid and, if so, the discounted prices for the given category.

# Scope

```python
@router.post("/promos/validate", response_model=PromoValidateResponse)
@limiter.limit(settings.rate_limit_promo_per_ip, key_func=get_remote_address)
async def validate_promo(request: Request, body: PromoValidateRequest):
    code = catalog.normalize_promo_code(body.code)
    if not code:
        return PromoValidateResponse(valid=False)
    label = catalog.promo_label(code)
    if label is None:
        return PromoValidateResponse(valid=False)
    # Build the discounted_prices map for the category
    services = catalog.SERVICES_MOTO if body.category == "MOTO" else catalog.SERVICES_WASH + catalog.SERVICES_DETAILING
    prices = {}
    for s in services:
        discounted = catalog.service_price(s.id, body.category, promo_code=code)
        public = catalog.public_service_price(s.id, body.category)
        if discounted < public:
            prices[s.id] = discounted
    return PromoValidateResponse(valid=True, label=label, discounted_prices=prices)
```

# Why 200 + valid=false (not 404)

A 404 on a public promo-validation endpoint would let an attacker confirm the existence of valid codes by absence-of-404. By always returning 200 with a boolean, we don't leak code existence to enumeration.

# Logging

INFO: `promos.validate code={code_or_'-'} category={category} valid={true_or_false} discounts_count={count}`.

# Tests (test_api_promo_validate.py)

- Valid `YS26` + car: `valid=true`, discounted_prices for ~10 services.
- Valid `YS26` + MOTO: `valid=true` but no discounts (moto is never discounted in this code base).
- Invalid `XYZ`: `valid=false`.
- Lowercase / whitespace input normalized: `"ys26 "` accepted.

# Acceptance criteria

- [ ] Endpoint always returns 200.
- [ ] Rate-limited per IP.
- [ ] All 4 tests pass.

# Context

The PWA needs to know where to send API requests. Production points at the Railway URL; local dev points at `http://localhost:8000`. Rather than hardcoding in `api.js`, use a tiny `config.js` so the API base is the FIRST thing that gets configured per-deployment.

# Scope

Create `mobile-app/config.js`:

```js
// Resolved order:
//   1. ?api=<url> query param (dev only)
//   2. Compile-time constant below (production default)
(function () {
  var params = new URLSearchParams(location.search);
  var override = params.get("api");
  var prodDefault = "https://ewash-agent-production.up.railway.app"; // TODO: confirm prod URL
  window.EWASH_API_BASE = override || prodDefault;
  if (override) {
    console.info("[ewash] API base overridden via ?api=", override);
  }
})();
```

# Why a separate file (not inline in app.jsx)

- It's plain `<script src>` not `type="text/babel"` — no JSX, doesn't need Babel.
- Easier for the deploy pipeline (or a future feature flag service) to swap the file without rebuilding JSX.
- Read by `api.js` (also plain) which loads BEFORE app.jsx kicks in.

# Tests (unit, via JSDOM or manual)

Practically untestable without a real browser. Manual smoke test: open `index.html?api=http://localhost:8000` and confirm `window.EWASH_API_BASE` is set correctly via DevTools console.

# Acceptance criteria

- [ ] `window.EWASH_API_BASE` is set before app.jsx runs.
- [ ] `?api=` override works for dev.
- [ ] Console logs the override when used.

# Context

A flaky network is the rule, not the exception, on mobile. Server-side validation can reject for many reasons. The PWA must handle every failure mode gracefully AND map specific server `error_code` values to specific UI affordances (highlighting the right field, etc.).

**New in this revision**: when the API is hard-down or persistently failing, expose a fallback CTA to message the staff WhatsApp directly. The customer's booking attempt doesn't die — it routes to a human.

# Scope — error UX matrix

| Server error_code | HTTP | UX outcome |
|-------------------|------|------------|
| `invalid_phone` | 400 | Stay on recap. Highlight phone field, inline message "Numéro invalide". |
| `service_category_mismatch` | 400 | Bounce back to service step. Toast "Service indisponible pour ce type de véhicule". |
| `unknown_service` | 400 | Bounce back to bootstrap refetch. Toast "Service introuvable, rechargement..." |
| `unknown_addon` / `duplicate_addon` / `not_a_detailing_service` | 400 | Bounce back to addons step. Toast "Option non disponible". |
| `unknown_center` / `missing_center_id` / `center_id_not_allowed` | 400 | Bounce back to location step. Toast "Stand non disponible". |
| `closed_date` | 400 | Bounce back to date step. Toast "Date fermée, choisissez une autre". |
| `unknown_slot` / `slot_too_soon` | 400 | Bounce back to time step. Toast "Créneau indisponible, choisissez une autre heure". |
| `invalid_date` | 400 | Bounce back to date step. Toast "Date invalide". |
| `rate_limit_exceeded` | 429 | Stay on recap. Toast + visible countdown for `Retry-After` seconds. Submit button disabled. |
| `validation_error` (Pydantic) | 422 | Stay on recap. Toast + include `field` from response for debugging. |
| `db_unavailable` | 503 | Stay on recap. Toast + WhatsApp fallback CTA. |
| `internal_error` | 500 | Stay on recap. Toast + WhatsApp fallback CTA after 2nd consecutive failure. |
| (network timeout / abort) | n/a | Stay on current step. Toast "Connexion lente. Réessayez." After 3 consecutive timeouts: WhatsApp fallback. |
| (offline, navigator.onLine=false) | n/a | Show dedicated `<OfflineCard />` with WhatsApp fallback. |

# WhatsApp fallback affordance

When the API is unreachable (offline OR persistent 5xx OR repeated timeouts), the PWA shouldn't dead-end. Show a CTA that opens WhatsApp with a pre-filled message containing the in-progress booking data:

```jsx
function WhatsAppFallback({ booking, t, staffContact }) {
  const phone = staffContact?.whatsapp_phone || "+212611204502";  // fallback default
  const lines = [
    "Bonjour, je n'arrive pas à finaliser ma réservation Ewash via l'application.",
    `Nom: ${booking.name}`,
    `Téléphone: ${booking.phone}`,
    `Véhicule: ${booking.category} - ${booking.make} ${booking.color}`.trim(),
    `Service: ${booking.service_label || booking.service}`,
    booking.date ? `Date souhaitée: ${booking.date}` : "",
    booking.time ? `Créneau: ${booking.time}` : "",
    booking.locationKind === "home"
      ? `Adresse: ${booking.pinAddress || "à confirmer"}`
      : "Au stand",
    booking.note ? `Note: ${booking.note}` : "",
  ].filter(Boolean).join("\n");
  const url = `https://wa.me/${phone.replace(/[^0-9]/g, "")}?text=${encodeURIComponent(lines)}`;
  return (
    <Btn onClick={() => { EwashLog.info("booking.whatsapp_fallback", { ref_attempt: booking.client_request_id }); window.open(url, "_blank"); }}>
      <Icon name="message-circle" />
      {t.booking.continueViaWhatsApp}
    </Btn>
  );
}
```

# When to show the WhatsApp fallback

- Always in the OfflineCard (since the customer is clearly offline and we can pre-fill the message from their in-progress data).
- After 2 consecutive `db_unavailable` or `internal_error` responses to POST /bookings.
- After 3 consecutive network timeouts on the main flow.

Don't show it on the first failure — be optimistic that the next retry succeeds.

# Implementation

```jsx
const [consecutiveFailures, setConsecutiveFailures] = useS_b(0);

function _handleApiError(err, currentStep, setStep, setFieldError, setToast, setConsecutiveFailures) {
  EwashLog.warn("booking.error", {
    step: currentStep,
    error_code: err.error_code,
    http_status: err.status,
    duration_ms: err.duration_ms,
    consecutive: consecutiveFailures + 1,
  });

  // Per-field handlers
  if (err.error_code === "invalid_phone") {
    setFieldError("phone", t.invalidPhone);
    return;
  }
  // Step-bounce handlers
  const bounceMap = {
    service_category_mismatch: "service",
    unknown_service: "service",
    unknown_addon: "addons",
    duplicate_addon: "addons",
    not_a_detailing_service: "addons",
    unknown_center: "location",
    missing_center_id: "location",
    center_id_not_allowed: "location",
    closed_date: "date",
    invalid_date: "date",
    unknown_slot: "time",
    slot_too_soon: "time",
  };
  if (bounceMap[err.error_code]) {
    setToast({ variant: "error", message: _toastFor(err.error_code) });
    setStep(bounceMap[err.error_code]);
    setConsecutiveFailures(0);
    return;
  }
  // 429 with countdown
  if (err.status === 429) {
    setToast({ variant: "warning", message: t.rateLimited });
    _disableSubmitFor(err.retry_after * 1000);
    setConsecutiveFailures(0);
    return;
  }
  // 5xx / network → consecutive failure counter
  const isInfra = err.status >= 500 || err.error_code === "network_error" || err.error_code === "timeout";
  if (isInfra) {
    setConsecutiveFailures(c => c + 1);
    setToast({ variant: "error", message: t.serviceTemporarilyDown });
    return;
  }
  // Default
  setToast({ variant: "error", message: t.submitErrorRetry });
}

// Render WhatsApp fallback when threshold hit
{consecutiveFailures >= 2 && staffContact?.available && (
  <WhatsAppFallback booking={data} t={t} staffContact={staffContact} />
)}
```

# Generic per-step error rendering

Every step component receives a `stepError` prop. When set, renders below the step content:

```jsx
function StepErrorBanner({ error, onRetry, showWhatsAppFallback, staffContact }) {
  if (!error) return null;
  return (
    <div className="step-error" role="alert">
      <Icon name="alert-circle" />
      <span>{error.message || t.errorGeneric}</span>
      {onRetry && <button onClick={onRetry}>{t.retry}</button>}
      {showWhatsAppFallback && <WhatsAppFallback booking={data} t={t} staffContact={staffContact} />}
    </div>
  );
}
```

# OfflineCard with fallback

```jsx
function OfflineCard({ t, booking, staffContact }) {
  return (
    <div className="offline-card">
      <Icon name="wifi-off" size={48} />
      <h2>{t.offlineTitle}</h2>
      <p>{t.offlineBody}</p>
      {staffContact?.available && booking?.phone && (
        <>
          <p className="muted">{t.offlineFallbackPrompt}</p>
          <WhatsAppFallback booking={booking} t={t} staffContact={staffContact} />
        </>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

