# Context

The PWA's service worker (`mobile-app/service-worker.js`) is **network-first with cache fallback** — fine for static assets, BUT not for API responses. Without bypass:
- Stale bookings list (the user's latest booking doesn't show on second app open).
- Stale catalog (admin price edits invisible to PWA until SW cache purge).
- Stale auth state (an invalidated token returns cached 200 responses).

The fix is an early return at the top of the fetch handler. It must apply to ALL HTTP methods (GET, POST, OPTIONS preflight) so even POST /bookings doesn't accidentally get cached.

# Scope

In `mobile-app/service-worker.js` fetch handler:

```js
self.addEventListener("fetch", (event) => {
  const url = new URL(event.request.url);

  // CRITICAL: bypass cache entirely for API paths.
  // Applies to all methods (GET cache-bypass, POST never touches cache anyway,
  // OPTIONS preflight needs the live CORS headers).
  if (url.pathname.startsWith("/api/")) {
    // Return without calling event.respondWith — the browser handles the
    // request normally without any SW involvement.
    return;
  }

  // Non-API requests: existing network-first cache-fallback logic
  if (event.request.method !== "GET") return;

  event.respondWith(
    fetch(event.request)
      .then((response) => {
        // Update cache in the background
        const clone = response.clone();
        caches.open(CACHE_NAME).then((cache) => cache.put(event.request, clone));
        return response;
      })
      .catch(() => caches.match(event.request))
  );
});
```

# Why ALL methods (not just GET)

- **POST /api/v1/bookings**: SW already bypasses cache for non-GET, but explicitly returning early covers cross-origin POSTs too.
- **OPTIONS preflight**: must go to the network to get live CORS headers — caching would serve stale headers after the admin updates `ALLOWED_ORIGINS`.

